800.74 on Nov 4, and still falling, recently by ~40 points/week. 4 more weeks of data left in the forecast period. The trend has been downward since Sept 2, so I'll forecast that that will probably largely continue through Nov.
Surprises are still possible, and price hikes related to some new LNG price shock are possible, but the index seems to be headed down.
Trending back to normal prices.

6 more weeks to go in the forecast period. 879.36 today, with a gently downward trend since Sept 2. I'll slightly narrow my forecast around bin 2, keeping in mind that the index can be extremely volatile.
right around 900
Slightly reducing my forecast on upper bins with the ongoing gentle decline. Volatility is still quite possible, though; 8 weeks left in the forecast.
10/11/2022: The Green Markets Weekly North America Fertilizer Price Index is at 890.47.
Around 900 is starting to look more likely after all.
Finally broke through 900 ceiling, looks to be the new support but not clearly established yet. Playing safe for few more weeks.

Based on where the index is now (921), where it was last year at this time (847), where it was last year around Dec 2 (1073), what last year's fall peak was (1118), what this year's peak was (1270), and the fact that the index has bounced around in the range of 821 to 983 since late May and isn't currently trending upward, I think it will likely end up in the range 975-1200 around Dec 2, and if I had to pick one number, I'd pick 1050. If there is some new energy crisis and the price of LNG skyrockets again, I think it could potentially end up higher. I can't picture it falling below 700 at this point, and the chance of seeing it below 900 even seems slim at this point. I expect the index to move generally a bit upwards in the remainder of the forecast period.
Demand for fertilizer should be lower in the winter months in the U.S.
The price already went to 1270, but what happens to fertilizer prices if we have a worldwide famine in 4Q2022?

I expect to see prices gradually decline until the fall. Then, I expect the energy situation to be a problem in late 2022, and I expect high natural gas prices to drive up fertilizer prices late in the year. I don't think last year's energy problems have been fully solved, and with Europe generally weaning itself from Russian oil and gas, I expect higher gas prices and hence fertilizer prices. And then there can always be some new, unanticipated shock.
Haven't dug into seasonality yet, that's not the primary X factor of likelihood at this point.
Time spent on forecast research: 2.5 hours

Zeroing out bin 5. I think if the invasion of Ukraine didn't push the index over 1300, then it would take a much larger conflict to do so, and I think the chance of that happening in the forecast period is <0.5%.

It increasingly looks like the recent price spike has ended and that prices are starting to fall again. I think somewhere in the range 800-850 is most likely, but I think anything around that could happen, too. I think it would take an unprecedentedly large shock to drive prices above 1300; even war in Ukraine didn't do that.
Fertilizer depends on natural gas prices... europe war crisis means higher prices, and possible future independization could also mean higher prices

Fertilizer prices largely depend on the price of oil. I'm not sure where that's going to go. The index has an underlying trend that has increased by about 32/month. If that continued as before (it almost surely won't), and barring price spikes, that would put the index at about 1183.
